, Suffolk, England":"Newmarket, Suffolk, England","Docking, Norfolk, England":"Docking, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Creke","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from North or South Creake in Norfolk, named from Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘cliff, rock’.","English: from Middle English <i>creke</i> ‘basket’ (Old French <i>creche</i>), hence a metonymic occupational name for a basket maker.","Americanized form of German   Krieg   or <b>Krück</b> (see   Kruck  ), or German and Jewish   Krick  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Krieg","meanings":["Swiss German, German, and Jewish (Ashkenazic): nickname for an argumentative person, from Middle High German, Middle Low German <i>kriec</i>, German <i>Krieg</i> ‘strife, conflict, squabble’ (Yiddish <i>krig</i>). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine).","German: variant of the plural form of   Krug  ."]},{"name":"Crick","meanings":["English: habitational name from Crick in Northamptonshire, from Celtic <i>creig</i> ‘rock, cliff’.","English: occasionally a topographic name for someone who lived by an inlet, from a Middle English borrowing of Old Norse <i>kriki</i>.","Possibly also an Americanized form of any of the German and Dutch surnames mentioned at   Creek   3."]},{"name":"Creeks","meanings":["English (Durham): variant of   Creek  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Robert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the many French names of Germanic origin that were introduced into Britain by the Normans; it has since remained in continuous use. It is derived from the nearly synonymous elements <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’, and had a native Old English predecessor of similar form (<i>Hreodbeorht</i>), which was supplanted by the Norman name. Two dukes of Normandy in the 11th century bore the name: the father of  William the Conqueror  (sometimes identified with the legendary Robert the Devil), and his eldest son. It was borne also by three kings of Scotland, notably  Robert the Bruce  (  1274–1329 ), who freed Scotland from English domination. The altered short form <i>Bob</i> is very common, but <i>Hob</i> and <i>Dob</i>, which were common in the Middle Ages and gave rise to surnames, are extinct.  See also  Rupert ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":52,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":61,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Robert